PCA¶

Before executing PCA, we need to standardize the variables.

In [11]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

Separate the inputs from the output.

In [12]:
xinputs = sonar_df.select_dtypes('number').copy()

youtput = sonar_df.loc[:, ['response']].copy()

Standardize the inputs.

In [13]:
Xsonar = StandardScaler().fit_transform( xinputs )
In [14]:
print( type(Xsonar) )

<class 'numpy.ndarray'>
In [15]:
sns.catplot(data = pd.DataFrame(Xsonar, columns=xinputs.columns), kind='box', aspect=3.5)

plt.show()

We can execute PCA by initializing the PCA() and "fitting" the object. When we first introduced PCA with clustering, we focused on just 2 components.

In [16]:
pca_object_2 = PCA(n_components=2).fit(Xsonar)
In [17]:
sonar_with_2_pcs = pca_object_2.transform(Xsonar)
In [18]:
sonar_with_2_pcs.shape
Out[18]:
(208, 2)

Instead allow for ALL PCs.

In [19]:
pca_object = PCA().fit(Xsonar)
In [20]:
sonar_pcs = pca_object.transform(Xsonar)
In [21]:
sonar_pcs.shape
Out[21]:
(208, 60)
In [22]:
print( type(sonar_pcs) )

<class 'numpy.ndarray'>

How many PCs?¶

The fraction of the variance explained per PC.

In [39]:
fraction_var_explain = pca_object.explained_variance_ratio_
In [40]:
print( type(fraction_var_explain) )

<class 'numpy.ndarray'>
In [41]:
pc_numbers = np.arange(len(fraction_var_explain)) + 1

pc_numbers

ax.plot(pc_numbers, fraction_var_explain, 'bo-')

ax.set_xlabel('PC')
ax.set_ylabel('variance explained ratio')

plt.show()

Total or cumulative variance explained.

In [44]:
total_var_explain = fraction_var_explain.cumsum()
In [46]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,8))

ax.plot(pc_numbers, total_var_explain, 'bo-')

ax.axhline(y=0.5, color='grey', linestyle='--')

ax.axhline(y=0.8, color='black', linestyle='--')

ax.axhline(y=0.95, color='red', linestyle='--')

ax.set_xlabel('PC')
ax.set_ylabel('total variance explained')

plt.show()
